posts.text:
Sunday Q&A: 
question was ‚ÄúHow do I separate the noise from valuable criticism that‚Äôs worthy of my attention?‚Äù 

Great question ‚ÄºÔ∏èüëèüèæ

Here‚Äôs two examples I‚Äôve experienced that taught me some great lessons, that sharpened my tools in differentiating the two. 

1) Me and my buddy joerogan 
Not only were we texting each other and shaking our heads while all that noise was going down a year or so ago - but the lesson was realizing that toxic noise makers actually don‚Äôt care about finding resolve or having meaningful dialogue that gets us to a good place of understanding one another. 
The noise makers, just want the attention and the clicks ‚Äî then a week later they‚Äôll move on to the next person or thing they can attach to - just to make more noise. 

2) the first 6 months of my rookie career in WWE. 
Every arena across the country went from chanting ‚ÄúROCKY‚Äù to ‚ÄúROCKY SUCKS‚Äù. Fun times üòÖ
Everyone told me ‚ÄúRock just ignore the negativity and keep smiling‚Äù. Well the more I smiled, the louder the Rocky Sucks chants got. 
I was in a real bad place mental health wise and ready to throw in the towel and quit WWE. One of my wrestling mentors, Pat Patterson said to me, ‚ÄúThey‚Äôre not chanting Rocky Sucks every night because they don‚Äôt like you. They‚Äôre chanting Rocky Sucks because you‚Äôre not being yourself‚Ä¶
Be YOU. The next time you go out in the that arena, be 100% Dwayne Johnson, The Rock‚Äù 

That‚Äôs exactly what I did. 
And the rest is history. 

And for me, that lesson‚òùüèæis two fold‚Äî 

I‚Äôll always be me and always be real 

And sometimes what can appear to be monumental noise, is actually invaluable criticism that is very worthy of your time. Trust your gut and listen to it. 

One last thing to take with you/

Haters can‚Äôt break what they didn‚Äôt build. 

Separate the noise, from valuable criticism and have a productive (and disruptive) week, my friends. 

Cheat meals await us üç∞ü•É

Chopping it up with joerogan about the summer of ‚Äò97 before I became ‚ÄúThe Rock‚Äù, my name was ‚ÄúRocky Maivia‚Äù - I just tore a ligament in my knee and my wwe career was completely failing as a rookie babyface. I started to consider a career in MMA with a new started fighting company, called PRIDE in Japan ‚Äî where the athletes were making some pretty big money. 

I thought I could take a year or so to commit to my MMA training and maybe I‚Äôd have shot. Maybe not. 
But I wanted to make some real money. 

At the end of that summer of ‚Äò97 I was rehabbing my injured knee and got the call from Vince McMahon that wound up changing my life ‚Äî he said I‚Äôm gonna bring you back BUT you‚Äôre gonna become a heel, join the Nation of Domination and call yourself The Rock. 

Thank God I got that call, because my career as an MMA fighter in PRIDE would‚Äôve lasted all of 3 minutes because those guys would‚Äôve knocked my fucking jaw across the pacific üòÇüíÄ

But the lesson of all this that I did learn, is that the most powerful thing you can be is yourself.
